[{"id":32227,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>7</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>8</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mo> </mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>A magnetic moment is a quantity that represents the magnetic strength and orientation of a magnet or any other object that produces a magnetic field. More precisely, a magnetic moment refers to a magnetic dipole moment, the component of the magnetic moment that can be represented by a magnetic dipole. The greater the number of unpaired electrons, the higher will be the magnetic moment.</p><p>Magnetic moment<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnlines=\"solid\" frame=\"solid\" rowlines=\"solid\"><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>7</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>8</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mtext> No. of. </mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtext> unpaired </mtext><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>2</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn></mtd><mtd><mn>4</mn></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><mtext> Spin only </mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtext> Magnetic </mtext></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtext> moment </mtext></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd><mtd><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msqrt><mn>15</mn></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>BM</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd><mtd><mtable><mtr><mtd><msqrt><mn>8</mn></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>BM</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd><mtd><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msqrt><mn>15</mn></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>BM</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd><mtd><mtable columnalign=\"left\"><mtr><mtd><msqrt><mn>24</mn></msqrt></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mi>BM</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32176,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{B}$","$\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{B}$","$\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{D}<\\mathrm{B}<\\mathrm{A}$","$\\mathrm{A}<\\mathrm{B}<\\mathrm{C}<\\mathrm{D}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The energy of a spectral line in the hydrogen atom is given by $E = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{n_1^2} - \\frac{1}{n_2^2} \\right)$ eV.<br>A. First line of Paschen series: $n_1 = 3, n_2 = 4$.<br>$E_A = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{3^2} - \\frac{1}{4^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{9} - \\frac{1}{16} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{7}{144} \\approx 0.66$ eV.<br><br>B. Second line of Balmer series: $n_1 = 2, n_2 = 4$.<br>$E_B = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{2^2} - \\frac{1}{4^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{16} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{16} = 2.55$ eV.<br><br>C. Third line of Paschen series: $n_1 = 3, n_2 = 6$.<br>$E_C = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{3^2} - \\frac{1}{6^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{9} - \\frac{1}{36} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{36} = 13.6 \\times \\frac{1}{12} \\approx 1.13$ eV.<br><br>D. Fourth line of Brackett series: $n_1 = 4, n_2 = 8$.<br>$E_D = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{4^2} - \\frac{1}{8^2} \\right) = 13.6 \\left( \\frac{1}{16} - \\frac{1}{64} \\right) = 13.6 \\times \\frac{3}{64} \\approx 0.6375$ eV.<br><br>Comparing the values: $E_D (0.6375) < E_A (0.66) < E_C (1.13) < E_B (2.55)$.<br>The ascending order of energy is $D < A < C < B$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32388,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sc}^{3+}$","$\\mathrm{Ba}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Sr}^{2+}, \\mathrm{K}^{+}, \\mathrm{S}^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{N}^{3-}, \\mathrm{O}^{2-}, \\mathrm{F}^{-}, \\mathrm{S}^{2-}$","$\\mathrm{Li}^{+}, \\mathrm{Na}^{+}, \\mathrm{Mg}^{2+}, \\mathrm{Ca}^{2+}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":32239,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5f9fac41-603d-44ce-8eaa-622c3a693c33.png\" style=\"width: 161px; height: 146px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/06f2ec32-19dc-4a2a-beb5-6a54353731e2.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 123px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fae2eed6-2d74-49fc-87b8-fd9eab94bc7f.png\" style=\"width: 173px; height: 138px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/288c17cc-8dde-4118-a5ab-74c0e5faaf03.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 137px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Moseley&#39;s observation on characteristic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>-ray spectra of elements relates frequency <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi><mo>)</mo></math> of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>-rays emitted to the atomic number by the following relation:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></math><br />The plot of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msqrt></math> vs <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></math> is linear.<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fae2eed6-2d74-49fc-87b8-fd9eab94bc7f.png\" style=\"width: 173px; height: 138px;\" /><br />Based on this observation, the periodic law defined as the physical and chemical properties of the elements are periodic functions of their atomic numbers.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32230,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Isoelectronic are those which have the&nbsp;same number of electrons. Let us write the number of electrons from the given species.</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Species</td>\t\t\t<td>No. of electrons</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mo>&#8211;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Mg</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mg</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Al</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>Hence five species among the given are isoelectronic species.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32225,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Noble gas configuration<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mi>ns</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>np</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mrow></mrow><mn>38</mn></msub><msup><mi>Sr</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>36</mn></msub><mi>Kr</mi><mo>]</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>54</mn></msub><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><msub><mi>Yb</mi><mn>70</mn></msub><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>54</mn></msub><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>14</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mrow></mrow><mn>57</mn></msub><msup><mi>La</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>54</mn></msub><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mrow></mrow><mn>82</mn></msub><msup><mi>Pb</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>54</mn></msub><mi>Xe</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>14</mn></msup><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>10</mn></msup><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><msub><mrow></mrow><mn>26</mn></msub><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>[</mo><mn>18</mn></msub><mi>Ar</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>6</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> and  <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Sr</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> have noble gas configuration, which are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Xe</mi><mo> </mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Kr</mi></math>, respectively.</p><p>Hence, the answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32282,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>","Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","Only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;both"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The orbitals which have same energy are called&nbsp;degenerate orbitals. Energy or an orbital depends on two quantum numbers, principle quantum number (n) and azimuthal quantum number (l).</p><p>The orbitals with similar values of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math> but with different value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>&nbsp;will be degenerate orbitals.</p><p>Among the given set or orbital only option (B)&nbsp;fulfil this condition.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32232,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mi>th</mi></math>&nbsp;of the value","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>27</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;of this value","<p>Three times of this value</p>","<p>One third of this value</p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The energy of an electron in the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi>th</mi></msup></math> Bohr orbit of a hydrogen atom can be calculated using the formula:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>18</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>Where</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>is</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>principal</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>quantum</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>the</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Bohr</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>orbit</mi><mo>.</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Therefore, the energy of the electron in the third Bohr orbit of a hydrogen atom is&nbsp;Three times of this value.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32196,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":2,"solution":"For a shell total number of orbitals $=n^2$\nMagnetic quantum number have values $(-\\ell$ to $+\\ell)$ including 0 .","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32175,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$9.835 \\times 10^{12}$","$1.635 \\times 10^{-18}$","$1.635 \\times 10^{-11}$","$9.835 \\times 10^{5}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The energy of an electron in the $n^{th}$ Bohr orbit of a hydrogen atom is given by $E_n = -R_H \\left( \\frac{1}{n^2} \\right)$.<br>The energy required for excitation from $n=1$ to $n=2$ for a single atom is $\\Delta E = E_2 - E_1 = R_H \\left( \\frac{1}{1^2} - \\frac{1}{2^2} \\right) = R_H \\left( 1 - \\frac{1}{4} \\right) = \\frac{3}{4} R_H$.<br>Given $R_H = 2.18 \\times 10^{-11}$ ergs.<br>Converting ergs to Joules: $1 \\text{ erg} = 10^{-7} \\text{ J}$.<br>So, $R_H = 2.18 \\times 10^{-11} \\times 10^{-7} = 2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ J}$.<br>The energy required per atom is $\\Delta E = \\frac{3}{4} \\times 2.18 \\times 10^{-18} = 1.635 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ J}$.<br>To find the energy required per mole of electrons, multiply by Avogadro's number $N_A \\approx 6.022 \\times 10^{23} \\text{ mol}^{-1}$.<br>Energy per mole $= 1.635 \\times 10^{-18} \\times 6.022 \\times 10^{23} \\text{ J mol}^{-1}$.<br>Energy per mole $\\approx 9.846 \\times 10^5 \\text{ J mol}^{-1}$.<br>Comparing with the given options, $9.835 \\times 10^5$ is the closest value.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32194,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["B and C Only","A and B Only","C and D Only","D and E Only"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{array}{lc} \\mathrm{A}: \\mathrm{n}=1, \\ell=0, \\mathrm{~m}_{\\ell}=0 & 1 \\mathrm{~s} \\\\ \\mathrm{B}: \\mathrm{n}=2, \\ell=0, \\mathrm{~m}_{\\ell}=0 & 2 \\mathrm{~s} \\\\ \\mathrm{C}: \\mathrm{n}=3, \\ell=1, \\mathrm{~m}_{\\ell}=1 & 3 \\mathrm{p} \\\\ \\mathrm{D}: \\mathrm{n}=3, \\ell=2, \\mathrm{~m}_{\\ell}=1 & 3 \\mathrm{~d} \\\\ \\mathrm{E}: \\mathrm{n}=3, \\ell=2, \\mathrm{~m}_{\\ell}=0 & 3 \\mathrm{~d} \\\\ \\end{array}$\r\nIn absence of electric and magnetic fields, all orbitals of 3d are degenerate","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32346,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Lyman series","Balmer series","Brackett series","Paschen series"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>211</mn><mo>.6</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>pm</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.11</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8491;</mi></math>.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.529</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.11</mo><mo>&#8491;</mo><mo>.</mo></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32215,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WaIA_JOtKXZ-xr5Vsh-WOOxJwj_BTMnnd-CfYo5w2LY.original.fullsize.png\"><br />So answer is 4 .","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32166,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$\\frac{7 \\mathrm{R}}{144}, \\frac{3 \\mathrm{R}}{16}, \\frac{16 \\mathrm{R}}{255}$","$\\frac{5 \\mathrm{R}}{36}, \\frac{8 \\mathrm{R}}{9}, \\frac{15 \\mathrm{R}}{16}$","$\\frac{3 \\mathrm{R}}{4}, \\frac{3 \\mathrm{R}}{16}, \\frac{7 \\mathrm{R}}{144}$","$\\frac{5 \\mathrm{R}}{36}, \\frac{3 \\mathrm{R}}{16}, \\frac{21 \\mathrm{R}}{100}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For the Balmer series, transitions end at n=2.<br>Using the Rydberg formula $\\bar{\\nu} = R\\left(\\frac{1}{2^2} - \\frac{1}{n^2}\\right) = R\\left(\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{n^2}\\right)$, we calculate wavenumbers for transitions from different upper levels: <br>From n=3: $\\bar{\\nu} = R\\left(\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{9}\\right) = \\frac{5R}{36}$ <br>From n=4: $\\bar{\\nu} = R\\left(\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{16}\\right) = \\frac{3R}{16}$ <br>From n=5: $\\bar{\\nu} = R\\left(\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{25}\\right) = \\frac{21R}{100}$ <br>Option (4) contains exactly these three wavenumbers corresponding to the Balmer series transitions.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32322,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced></math> option is correct.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#957;</mi><mo>-</mo></mover><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><br />For balmer series,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br />For the longest wavelength, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#175;</mo></mover></math>,<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32343,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$4 \\times 0.529 Å$","$2 \\pi \\times 0.529 Å$","$\\frac{0.529}{2 \\pi} Å$","$0.529 Å$"],"answer":1,"solution":"First Bohr orbit of $\\mathrm{H}$ atom has radius\n$$\n\\mathrm{r}=0.529 Å\n$$\nAlso, the angular momentum is quantised.\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&\\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\pi} \\\\\n&2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\mathrm{mv}}=\\lambda \\\\\n&\\lambda=2 \\pi \\times 0.529 Å\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":32224,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Electronic configuration of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Rb</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mi>Kr</mi></mfenced><mn>5</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Rb</mi></math> is alkali metal with valence electron in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> subshell. Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Rb</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>[</mo><mi>Kr</mi><mo>]</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>1</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Hence, the answer is option A,</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32160,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$n = 3, l = 2, m = +2, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 3, l = 2, m = -2, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 4, l = 1, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","$n = 4, l = 0, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The atomic number of Chromium is $24$.<br><br>According to the Aufbau principle, the order of filling of electrons is $1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d$.<br><br>The electronic configuration of the first $18$ electrons is $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^6$.<br><br>The $19^{th}$ electron enters the $4s$ orbital.<br><br>For the $4s$ orbital, the quantum numbers are:<br>Principal quantum number, $n = 4$<br>Azimuthal quantum number, $l = 0$<br>Magnetic quantum number, $m = 0$<br>Spin quantum number, $s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$ or $-\\dfrac{1}{2}$<br><br>This matches the set given in the fourth option.<br><br>Answer: $n = 4, l = 0, m = 0, s = +\\dfrac{1}{2}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (04 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32157,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A, B and C Only","A, B and D Only","B, C and D Only","A, C and D Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement A is correct. Heisenberg's uncertainty principle is applicable to microscopic particles such as electrons.<br><br>Statement B is correct. The size of an orbital increases with an increase in the principal quantum number $n$. Thus, the size of the $3p_x$ orbital is greater than that of the $2p_x$ orbital.<br><br>Statement C is incorrect. The energy of an orbital depends on the effective nuclear charge. Since the nuclear charge of Li ($Z=3$) is greater than that of H ($Z=1$), the energy of the $2s$ orbital of Li is lower than that of the $2s$ orbital of H.<br><br>Statement D is correct. Chromium ($Z=24$) has an anomalous electronic configuration of $[\\text{Ar}] 3d^5 4s^1$ due to the extra stability of the half-filled $d$-subshell.<br><br>Therefore, statements A, B, and D are correct.<br><br>Answer: A, B and D Only","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32233,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The distance between the nucleus and&nbsp;5f&nbsp;orbital is more than the distance between the nucleus and&nbsp;4f&nbsp;orbital.&nbsp;Hence the hold of nucleus on valence electron decrease in 5f orbital. 5f orbital not buried as 4f oribitals so electron present in 5f orbital experience less nuclear attraction than electron present in 4f orbital. Hence electrons of 5f orbital can take part in bonding to far great extent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32262,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A circular path around the nucleus in which an electron moves is proposed as Bohr&#39;s orbit.","An orbital is the one electron wave function","The existence of Bohr&#39;s orbits is supported by hydrogen spectrum.","Atomic orbital is characterised by the quantum numbers <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>&nbsp;only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>An electron can move only in those orbits for which its angular momentum is integral multiple of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>. That means angular momentum is quantised. Radiation is emitted or absorbed only when transition of electron takes place from one quantised value of angular momentum to another. Therefore. Maxwell&#39;s electromagnetic theory does not apply here that is why only certain fixed orbits are allowed. Atomic orbital is characterised by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>. So, the option D is incorrect.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32320,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mn>6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mn>8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><mn>2</mn><mi></mi><mi>π</mi><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>λ</mi></math>  <br/><math><mn>2</mn><mi></mi><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>λ</mi></math>  <br/><math><mn>2</mn><mi></mi><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><msub><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>λ</mi></math>  <br/><math><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mi></mi><mi>π</mi><msub><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32259,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Heisenberg&#39;s uncertainty principle</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;x</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>&#916;p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>&#8805;</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>m&#916;v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>(minimum)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>&#916;v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>31</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>548273</mn><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>548</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>273</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>548</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>km</mi><msup><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32191,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{r} \\propto \\mathrm{q}^{-}$(for isoelectronic species)\n$\\propto \\frac{1}{q^{+}}$\n$\\therefore$ Statement I is correct\nMagnitude of electron gain enthalpy\n$\\mathrm{Cl}>\\mathrm{F}>\\mathrm{Br}>\\mathrm{I}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32247,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ion, the wave number associated with the Balmer transition,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;is given by:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>RZ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msup><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mstyle></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></math>&nbsp;= atomic number of helium</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#955;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>According to the question, the desired transition for hydrogen&nbsp;will have the same wavelength as that of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>&#955;</mi><mfenced><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>By hit and trial method,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math></p><p>On comparing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>So, the correct answer is n = 2 to n = 1.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32195,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["(B), (C) and (D) only","(A) and (E) only","(A) only","(B) only"],"answer":0,"solution":"For hydrogen atom and one electron species, the energy of orbitals is decided by the value of principal quantum number. Higher the value of principal quantum number, higher will be the energy of orbital.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fstUS9oO8QPYOzjhOvqm5wexyAO_x8nswGdc3x72Pzo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n$\\therefore \\quad(B),(C)$ and (D) have orbitals with the lowest energy.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32197,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/02bTAshMoyZWJ8t6mT2BnX-qnFxBIhfOsqBBRfNWU2g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (23 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32173,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["$+2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\mathrm{~J} \\text { for second orbit of } \\mathrm{He}^{+} \\text {ion }$","$-2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\mathrm{~J} \\text { for third orbit of } \\mathrm{Li}^{2+} \\text { ion }$","$-1.09 \\times 10^{-18} \\mathrm{~J} \\text { for second orbit of } \\mathrm{H} \\text { atom. }$","$+8.72 \\times 10^{-18} \\mathrm{~J} \\text { for first orbit of } \\mathrm{He}^{+} \\text {ion }$"],"answer":1,"solution":"The energy of an electron in the $n^{th}$ stationary state of a one-electron system is given by the Bohr's formula:<br>$E_n = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\times \\frac{Z^2}{n^2}$ J<br>where $Z$ is the atomic number and $n$ is the principal quantum number.<br>For option (1): Second orbit of $He^+$ ($Z=2, n=2$)<br>$E = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\times \\frac{2^2}{2^2} = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18}$ J. (Incorrect sign in option)<br>For option (2): Third orbit of $Li^{2+}$ ($Z=3, n=3$)<br>$E = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\times \\frac{3^2}{3^2} = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18}$ J. (Correct)<br>For option (3): Second orbit of $H$ atom ($Z=1, n=2$)<br>$E = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\times \\frac{1^2}{2^2} = -0.545 \\times 10^{-18}$ J. (Incorrect value)<br>For option (4): First orbit of $He^+$ ($Z=2, n=1$)<br>$E = -2.18 \\times 10^{-18} \\times \\frac{2^2}{1^2} = -8.72 \\times 10^{-18}$ J. (Incorrect sign in option)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32394,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["12 and 4","16 and 5","16 and 4","12 and 5"],"answer":3,"solution":"$24 \\longrightarrow 1 s^2 2 s^2 2 p^6 3 s^2 3 p^6 4 s^1 3 d^5$\n$I=1 \\rightarrow p \\longrightarrow 12$\n$I=2 \\rightarrow d \\longrightarrow 5$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":32294,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Structure of Atom","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Total energy provided by&nbsp;</p><p>Source per second <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p>Energy required to eject electron <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>hc</mi><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></math></p><p>Number of electrons ejected</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>26</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>40</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>626</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>20</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null}]